  "text": "[42] A thermal anomaly associated with diking would not be long-lived. Conductive cooling models predict that the anomaly would last at most 100 years for a dike swarm of width 45 m, but hydrothermal cooling would likely shorten that time span to as little as $9 years. Though a wider dike swarm would produce a longer-lived thermal anomaly, we expect the span of feeder dikes to be no wider than the 40-50 m width of the drained lava lake trough of the most recent eruption (we do not expect heat to remain from previous swarms since cooling times even for wider dike swarms are still less than a few dozen years, and they would have had to erupt several hundred years ago given the local spreading rate). A timescale of $9 years is marginally possible considering known constraints of eruptive history at these locales (summary above) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Haymon et al., 1993] but is orders of magnitude away from what is needed to explain the field low at the >1800-year-old fossil trough at 18°14 0 S. In this case, the most likely scenario is that a swarm of cooled dikes remains beneath the fossil trough, creating a magnetic field low because of their crystalline structure.",
